## Reference Management

### Tool Requirements

| Capability | Required | Tools |
|-----------|----------|-------|
| BibTeX export | Yes | Zotero, Mendeley, manual |
| DOI auto-lookup | Recommended | Zotero, doi2bib |
| Duplicate detection | Recommended | Zotero, JabRef |
| Shared library | For teams | Zotero groups, shared .bib file |

### Reference File Standards

- [ ] All references in a single `.bib` file (or managed by reference tool)
- [ ] BibTeX keys follow consistent naming: `author_year_keyword`
- [ ] No orphan references (every entry is cited somewhere)
- [ ] No missing fields (title, author, year, DOI minimum)
- [ ] References are sorted alphabetically by key

---

## Citation in Code

### Inline Code Citations

```python
# Algorithm from: Smith et al. (2023), "Fast Attention Mechanism"
# DOI: 10.xxxx/yyyy, Section 3.2
# Modifications: adapted for batch processing, added gradient checkpointing
def fast_attention(q, k, v):
    ...
```

### Citation Checklist for Code

- [ ] Every non-trivial algorithm has a source citation in comments
- [ ] Modifications from the cited source are documented
- [ ] License of cited code is compatible with project license
- [ ] Third-party code is in separate files or clearly delineated

---

## Verification Checklist

- [ ] All DOIs resolve correctly (automated check)
- [ ] All URLs are accessible (automated check with archive.org fallback)
- [ ] Dataset versions match what was actually used
- [ ] Software versions in citations match `requirements.txt`
- [ ] No uncited external contributions
- [ ] Reference list is complete and free of duplicates
